          "body": "The chapter records at least five distinct verdicts on Jesus, none neutral: His brothers do not believe (7:5); some in the crowd say *He is a good man* (7:12); others say *He deceives the people* (7:12); some say *this certainly is the Prophet* (7:40); others say *this is the Christ* (7:41); still others reject Him on Galilean grounds (7:41-42); the Pharisees pronounce the crowd *accursed* (7:49); the officers say *never has a man spoken the way this man speaks* (7:46). John's narrative point is that *a division (schisma) occurred in the crowd because of Him* (7:43) — Jesus is the wedge, not the misunderstanding. The chapter forces the reader to recognize that there is no available position called *no opinion*. Even Nicodemus, who defends due process (7:50-51), is mocked by his peers. The chapter is a sustained demonstration of John 1:11 — *He came to His own, and those who were His own did not receive Him* — with the partial exception of *many of the crowd* (7:31) and the future-tense confession of the brothers (Acts 1:14)."
