          "body": "Embedded in the temple controversy is one of the most theologically dense single verses in the Gospels: *if anyone is willing to do His will, he will know of the teaching, whether it is of God or whether I speak from Myself* (7:17). Jesus reverses the order the crowd assumes. They want to verify His teaching by independent investigation and then decide whether to obey. Jesus insists the order runs the other way: the willingness to do God's will is the precondition of recognizing whether teaching is from God. Calvin (*Commentary on John*) calls this the rule of true discernment — the proud, even if they study, will not see; the humble, even if untrained, will. Carson (*The Gospel According to John*, PNTC) emphasizes that the test is not perfect obedience but *willingness to obey* — a settled disposition of the heart toward God's revealed will. The verse explains why the unbelieving rulers, who possess the law, cannot recognize the One the law foretells, while the unschooled crowd is closer to faith."
