          "title": "The great-day invitation and the not-yet-given Spirit (7:37-39)",
          "body": "The chapter's theological climax is Jesus standing in the temple on the festival's last day and crying out — *krazo*, the verb of public proclamation — *if anyone is thirsty, let him come to Me and drink* (7:37). The grammar of verse 38 is debated. The traditional reading (NASB, ESV) makes the believer's inner being the source of rivers: *he who believes in Me, from his innermost being will flow rivers of living water*. The alternative punctuation, defended by D. A. Carson and others, puts the comma differently — *let the one who believes in Me drink; as the Scripture said, from His innermost being shall flow rivers of living water* — making *Jesus* the source. The Christological reading better fits the chapter's whole logic: Jesus is the rock from whom water flows (cf. 1 Corinthians 10:4), the Spirit-giver who must first be glorified. Either way, verse 39 leaves no ambiguity about the referent: *this He spoke of the Spirit, whom those who believed in Him were to receive*. The Booths water-ceremony, the prophecies of Ezekiel 47 and Zechariah 14, and the Pentecost outpouring are gathered into one chord — and conditioned on the cross-resurrection-ascension still to come."
